  <historical>
  <title>Emmy Noether</title>
  <image source="../../images/Noether.jpg" width="50%">
    <shortdescription>Portrait of Emmy Noether</shortdescription>
  </image>
  <p>
    In the 1920s, Emmy Noether was the first to explicitly describe the ring axioms as we know them today,
    and her definition of a (not-necessarily-commutative) ring has led to a great deal of interesting work in algebra,
    number theory, and geometry, including the
    (see <xref ref="Sec-Nonunique-Factorization" />
    for more on the historical development of the proof of Fermat's Last Theorem).
    Most modern definitions of <em>ring</em>
    agree with our <xref ref="def_ring">Definition</xref>
    and allow for rings with noncommutative multiplication.
  </p>
  </historical>

  <p>
    The following theorem states that the set of polynomials with coefficients in a ring <m>R</m> is itself a ring under the usual 
    operations of polynomial addition of like terms, and multiplication via distribution.
    The proof is not tricky, but a rigorous justification (especially of, e.g., the associativity of polynomial multiplication)
    is tedious, and thus is omitted.
  </p>
  <theorem xml:id="thm_polynomialsFormRing">
  <title>Theorem</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>R</m> is a (commutative) ring, then <m>R[x]</m> is a (commutative) ring.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      As in the proof of <xref ref="prop_polynomialMultiplicationIsCommutative"/>, we see that if <m>R[x]</m> is a ring and <m>R</m> is commutative, then 
      <m>R[x]</m> must also be commutative. The proof carries over <em>mutatis mutandis</em>.
    </p>
    <p>
      To see that <m>R[x]</m> is a ring, we need to check all eight axioms. Before we do that, recall in <xref ref="prop_polynomialAdditionIsCommutative"/> 
      that we have already seen polynomial addition is commutative provided the addition of coefficients is commutative. That proof therefore carries over 
      <em>mutatis mutandis</em>.
    </p>
    <p>
      We check associativity. Take <m>p(x),q(x),r(x)\in R[x]</m> and, by extending by 0, we can assume 
      <md>
        <mrow> p(x)\amp= a_0+a_1x+\cdots +a_nx^n </mrow>
        <mrow> q(x)\amp= b_0+b_1x+\cdots +b_nx^n </mrow>
        <mrow> r(x)\amp= c_0+r_1x+\cdots +r_nx^n </mrow>
      </md>
      where <m>a_i,b_i,c_i\in R</m> for <m>i=0,\ldots,n</m>. Then the coefficient of <m>x^i</m> in <m>p(x)+(q(x)+r(x))</m> 
      is <m>a_i+(b_i+c_i)</m>. The coefficient of <m>x^i</m> in <m>(p(x)+q(x)) + r(x)</m> is <m> (a_i+b_i)+c_i</m>. 
      Since <m>R</m> is a ring and addition is associative in <m>R</m> we have <m>a_i+(b_i+c_i) = (a_i+b_i) + c_i</m>. Since 
      the coefficients of <m>p(x)+(q(x)+r(x))</m> and <m>(p(x)+q(x)) + r(x)</m> are equal, they are equal polynomials.
    </p>

    <p>
      We claim <m>z(x) = 0_R</m> is the additive identity. Take <m>p(x)\in R[x]</m> and write 
      <me>p(x)=a_0+a_1x+\cdots +a_nx^n.</me>
      Then extend <m>z(x)</m> by zero:
      <me>z(x) = 0_R + 0_Rx+\cdots + 0_Rx^n.</me>
      The sum is then:
      <md>
        <mrow> z(x)+p(x)\amp= (0_R+a_0) + (0_R+a_1)x+\cdots + (0_R+a_n)x^n </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp= a_0 + a_1x+\cdots + a_nx^n </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp= p(x) </mrow>
      </md>
      as <m>0_R</m> is the additive identity in <m>R</m> so that <m>0_R+a_i = a_i</m> for all <m>i</m>. 
      Similarly, <m>p(x) + z(x) = p(x)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      For additive inverses, suppose <m>p(x)</m> is as before. Then define <m>-p(x)\in R[x]</m> by:
      <m>-p(x) = (-a_0) + (-a_1)x + \cdots + (-a_n)x^n</m>
      where <m>-a_i</m> is the additive inverse of the coefficient <m>a_i</m> in <m>p(x)</m>. Then 
      <md>
        <mrow> \amp p(x)+(-p)(x)</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp= (a_0+(-a_0)) + (a_1+(-a_1))x + \cdots + (a_n+(-a_n))x^n </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp= 0_R + 0_Rx + \cdots + 0_Rx^n </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp= z(x) </mrow>
      </md>
      Similarly <m>(-p)(x)+p(x) = z(x)</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The proof that multiplication is associative is particularly notationally dense and we leave it as an exercise.
      For the multiplicative identity, set <m>i(x) = 1_R</m>. Take a polynomial <m>p(x)</m> as before. We extend <m>i(x)</m> 
      by zero via:
      <me>
        i(x) = b_0+\cdots +b_nx^n
      </me>
      where <m>b_0=1_R</m> and <m>b_i=0_R</m> for <m>i>0</m>. Then the product
      <me>
        p(x)\cdot i(x)= c_0+c_1x+\cdots +c_nx^n
      </me>
      where
      <me>
        c_i = a_0b_i+\cdots + a_ib_0.
      </me>
      However, <m>b_j=0</m> for <m>j>0</m> so for <m>k\neq i</m> we have <m>a_kb_{i-k}=0_R</m> by Exercise???? In particular, <m>c_i = a_ib_0 = a_i\cdot 1_R = a_i</m>.
      Since the coefficients of <m>p(x)\cdot i(x)</m> and <m>p(x)</m> are equal, the polynomials are equal: <m>p(x)\cdot i(x) = p(x)</m>. 
      Similarly <m>i(x)\cdot p(x)= p(x)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The remaining two proofs are left- and right-distributive properties. As they are similar, we only prove the left-distributive property. TBD.
    </p>
  </proof>
</theorem>
<p>
  The preceeding theorem says that whenever we have a ring, polynomials with coefficients in that ring again form a ring. In particular, if <m>R</m> is a ring, then 
  so is <m>R[x]</m>, and hence so is <m>(R[x])[y]</m> and so on. This leads us to the corollary:
</p>
<corollary xml:id="cor_multivariatePolynomialRingIsARing">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>R</m> be a (commutative) ring and <m>x_1,\ldots,x_n</m> be indeterminates. Then the set of 
      polynomials in <m>x_1,\ldots,x_n</m> with coefficients in <m>R</m>, <m>R[x_1,\ldots,x_n]</m>, is a (commutative) ring.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      We proceed by induction. The base case is <m>n=1</m>. This is the content of <xref ref="thm_polynomialsFormRing"/>.
    </p>
    <p>
      For the inductive step, suppose <m>R[x_1,\ldots,x_n]</m> is a (commutative) ring. By <xref ref="thm_polynomialsFormRing"/>, 
      <m>R[x_1,\ldots,x_n][x_{n+1}]</m> is again a (commutative) ring. But the latter is the <m>R[x_1,\ldots,x_{n+1}]</m>.
    </p>
  </proof>
</corollary>

