<p>
  We now have some great examples of commutative rings. Namely polynomial rings in some number of variables over any of <m>\Z,\Q,\R,</m> or <m>\C</m>. 
  As we have yet to see an example of a non-commutative ring we remedy this now.
</p>

<example xml:id="ex_M2R">
  <title>Square Matrices</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the set <m>M_2(\R)</m> of square <m>2\times 2</m> matrices over <m>\R</m> (or whatever ring or field you like to work with). 
      We recall matrix addition and multiplication:
      <me>
        \begin{bmatrix}a_1 \amp b_1 \\ c_1 \amp d_1 \end{bmatrix} 
        + \begin{bmatrix}a_2 \amp b_2 \\ c_2 \amp d_2 \end{bmatrix}
        = \begin{bmatrix}(a_1+a_2) \amp (b_1+b_2) \\ (c_1+c_2) \amp (d_1+d_2) \end{bmatrix}
      </me>
      and 
      <me>
        \begin{bmatrix}a_1 \amp b_1 \\ c_1 \amp d_1 \end{bmatrix} 
        \cdot \begin{bmatrix}a_2 \amp b_2 \\ c_2 \amp d_2 \end{bmatrix}
        = \begin{bmatrix} a_1a_2+b_1c_2 \amp a_1b_2+b_1d_2 \\ c_1a_2+d_1c_2 \amp c_1b_2+d_1d_2 \end{bmatrix}
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      In Exercise???? you will check this is a ring. We show that multiplication is not commutative. To that end, consider:
      <me>
        A=\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix},
        B =\begin{bmatrix}0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}.
      </me>
      Then 
      <me>
        A\cdot B = \begin{bmatrix}0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix},
        B\cdot A = \begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}.
      </me>
      In particular, <m>A\cdot B\ne B\cdot A</m> and so matrix multiplication is not commutative.
    </p>
  </statement>
</example>

<p>
  In the previous example, we observed that matrix multiplication failed to be commutative for matrices with real entries. What about 
  for entries in a general ring? If you review that example, you will notice the only reason the products did not agree is because <m>0\ne 1</m> in <m>\R</m>.
  The next example shows that the multiplicative identity and additive identity sometimes agree.
</p>

<example>
  <title>The Zero Ring</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>R=\{0\}</m>. That is, a set with one element. Define addition and multiplication by 
      <m>0+0 = 0</m> and <m>0\cdot 0 = 0</m>. We claim that addition and multiplication define a ring structure 
      on <m>R</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Almost all of the checks are straightforward. For example, to check associativity of addition we 
      only have one element so we just check <m>0+(0+0) = (0+0)+0</m>. But there is only one thing both sides can be: <m>0</m>. 
      So addition is associative.
    </p>
    <p>
      The only property that warrants inspection is the multiplicative identity. We claim that in this ring <m>1_R = 0</m>. Indeed, 
      we need to show that for every <m>r\in R = \{0\}</m> that <m>0\cdot r= r</m>. But there's only element to check this on: <m>r=0</m> where it is true.
    </p>
    <p>
      We conclude that the zero ring is a ring!
    </p>
  </statement>
</example>
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="ssec_subrings">
  <title>Subrings: New Rings from Old</title>
  <definition>
  <idx>subring</idx>
  <idx>overring</idx>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>(R,+,\cdot)</m> be a ring and let <m>S\subseteq R</m>.
        If <m>S</m> is itself a ring under <m>+</m> and <m>\cdot</m>,
        we say <m>S</m> is a <term>subring</term> of <m>R</m>.
        In this case, <m>R</m> is often called an
        <term>overring</term> of <m>S</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    The following theorem provides a easy-to-apply test to check if a given subset <m>S</m> of a ring <m>R</m> is in fact a subring of <m>R</m>.
  </p>
  <theorem xml:id="thm_subringTest">
    <title>Subring Test</title>
  <idx>subring test</idx>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>R</m> be a ring and <m>S</m> a subset of <m>R</m>.
        Then <m>S</m> is a subring if and only if:
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>1_R\in S</m>;
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>S</m> is closed under multiplication; and
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>S</m> is closed under subtraction.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>1_R\in S</m> and <m>S</m> is closed under multiplication and subtraction. We check each of the axioms in <xref ref="def_ring"/>. 
        Since <m>1_R\in S</m> and <m>S</m> is closed under subtraction we have <m>0_R = 1_R-1_R\in S</m>. For any <m>a\in S</m>, we know that <m>a\in R</m> so that 
        <me>
          a+0_R = 0_R+a=a\text{ and }a\cdot 1_R = 1_R\cdot a = a.
        </me>
        Thus <m>0_R</m> and <m>1_R</m> are the additive and multiplicative identities, respectively, in <m>S</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        For any <m>b\in S</m>, we know that <m>-b=0_R-b\in S</m>. Thus <m>S</m> is closed under additive inverses. If <m>a,b\in S</m>, then <m>a+b=a-(-b)\in S</m> so that <m>S</m> is closed under addition.
      </p>
      <p>
        For any triple of elements <m>a,b,c\in S</m>, we know <m>a,b,c\in R</m> so that <m>a+(b+c) = (a+b)+c</m> and <m>a+b=b+a</m>. Thus associativity and commutativity of addition are inherited from <m>R</m>. 
        Similarly, <m>a\cdot(b\cdot c) = (a\cdot b)\cdot c</m>, <m>a\cdot(b+c) = a\cdot b + a\cdot c</m>, and <m>(a+b)\cdot c = a\cdot c + b\cdot c</m>. That is, <m>S</m> inherits associativity of multiplication as well as the left- and right-distributive properties from <m>R</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        We conclude that <m>S</m> is a ring under the multiplication and addition from <m>R</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        In <xref ref="ex_qAdjoinNegative5"/>, we saw that <m>\Q(\sqrt{-5})</m> was a field and so it is a commutative ring. 
        Let's define a subset of this field by taking 
        those elements with integral real and imaginary part:
        <me>
          \Z[\sqrt{-5}] = \{a+b\sqrt{-5}\mid a,b\in\Z\}.
        </me>
        We claim that <m>\Z[\sqrt{-5}]</m> is a subring of <m>\Q(\sqrt{-5})</m>. To that end we apply the subring test. That is,
        <m>1_{\Q(\sqrt{-5})}\in\Z[\sqrt{-5}]</m>, it is closed under subtraction and multiplication.
      </p>
      <p>
        We see that <m>1+0\sqrt{-5}\in\Z[\sqrt{-5}]</m> and so our subset has the multiplicative identity.
      </p>
      <p>
        For closure under subtraction, take <m>a+b\sqrt{-5}, c+d\sqrt{-5}\in\Z[\sqrt{-5}]</m>. Then 
        <me>
          (a+b\sqrt{-5})-(c+d\sqrt{-5}) = (a-c) + (b-d)\sqrt{-5}
        </me>
        and <m>a-c,b-d\in\Z</m>. We conclude <m>\Z[\sqrt{-5}]</m> is closed under subtraction.
      </p>
      <p>
        For closure under multiplication we compute:
        <me>
          (a+b\sqrt{-5})\cdot (c+d\sqrt{-5}) = (ac+5bd) + (ad+bc)\sqrt{-5}
        </me>
        and again <m>ac+5bd,ad+bc\in\Z</m>. 
      </p>
      <p>
        By the <xref ref="thm_subringTest" text="title"/>, we conclude <m>\Z[\sqrt{-5}]</m> is a subring of <m>\Q(\sqrt{-5})</m>. In particular, 
        it is a ring.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  
  <activity>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Determine whether the following rings <m>S</m> are subrings of the given rings <m>R</m>.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>S = \Z</m>, <m>R = \Q</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>S = \Z/5</m>, <m>R = \Z/7</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>S</m> is any ring, <m>R = S[x]</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>S = \R</m>, <m>R = \mathbb{C}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </activity>
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="ssec_unitsAndAssociates">
  <title>Units and Associates in a Ring</title>

  <definition xml:id="def_unit">
  <idx>unit</idx>
  <idx>associates</idx>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>R</m> be a ring and let <m>u\in R</m> be nonzero.
        If there is a <m>v\in R</m> such that <m>uv = vu = 1</m>,
        we say <m>u</m> is <term>unit</term> of <m>R</m>.
        We denote the set of units of <m>R</m> by <m>R^\times</m>.
        We say <m>x,y\in R</m> are <term>associates</term>
        if there exists some <m>u\in R^\times</m> such that <m>x = uy</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  
  <exploration>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Explicitly describe the set <m>\Z^\times</m>.
        What are the associates of 7 in <m>\Z</m>?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exploration>
  <p>
    In other words, a unit in a ring is a nonzero element with a multiplicative inverse.
    The existence of units is the primary difference between fields and commutative rings: in a field, all nonzero elements are units, while in a commutative ring, no nonzero elements need be units, as <xref ref="thm-cri-field" /> demonstrates.
  </p>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        We describe the units in <m>\Z[x]</m>. Notice that for <m>p(x)q(x)\in\Z[x]</m>, of degrees <m>m,n</m> respectively, 
        the leading coefficient of <m>p(x)\cdot q(x)</m> is
        <me>c_{m+n} = a_0b_{m+n} +a_1b_{m+n-1}+\dots + a_nb_m.</me>
        But <m>a_i = 0</m> for <m>i\ge </m> and <m>b_j=0</m> for <m>j\ge n</m>. Using this observation, we can conclude that <m>c_{m+n}=a_mb_n</m>, 
        see Exercise???? Since <m>a_m,b_n\ne 0</m> and the product of two non-zero integers remains non-zero, we conclude that <m>c_{m+n}\ne 0</m>. 
        In particular, 
        <me>
          \deg(p\cdot q) = \deg(p)+\deg(q).
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Now suppose that <m>p\cdot q = 1</m> in <m>\Z[x]</m>. Then 
        <md>
          <mrow> 0\amp=\deg(1) </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp=\deg(p\cdot q) </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp=\deg(p) + \deg(q). </mrow>
        </md>
        Since <m>\deg(p),\deg(q)\geq 0</m>, the only way this can happen is if <m>\deg(p) = \deg(q) = 0</m> so that <m>p,q</m> are constant polynomials. 
        Thus <m>p,q</m> are units in <m>\Z</m>. We conclude
        <me>
          \Z[x]^\times = \Z^\times = \{\pm 1\}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <theorem xml:id="thm-cri-field">
    <statement>
      <p>
        A commutative ring <m>R</m> in which every nonzero element is a unit is a field.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Compare the axioms for a commutative ring and a field.
      The only thing missing from the ring axioms is the existence of multiplicative inverses for nonzero elements.
    </p>
  </proof>

  <exercises xml:id="exers_rings">
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Mark the following as true or false.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              All fields are rings.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              All rings are fields.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              All rings are commutative.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Addition in any ring is commutative and associative.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Multiplication in any ring is commutative and associative.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              In a ring, the left- and right-distibutive laws hold.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              In a ring, only the left-distributive law is guaranteed to hold.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              All rings are rngs, but not all rngs are rings.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\Z</m> is a ring with the usual operations of addition and multiplication.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\Q</m> is a ring with the usual operations of addition and multiplication.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\R</m> is a ring with the usual operations of addition and multiplication.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>M_2(\Q)</m> is a ring with the usual operations of addition and multiplication.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the polynomial ring with integer coefficients <m>\mathbb{Z}[x]</m>. Prove that the left- and right-distributive laws hold. 
          You can use that polynomial multiplication is commutative to simplify some of your work.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="exer_gaussianIntegers">
      <title>Gaussian Integers</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>Gaussian Integers</term> are the subset of <m>\C</m> given by
          <me>\Z[i] = \{a+bi\in \C\mid a,b,\in\Z\}.</me>
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Using the usual addition and multiplication in <m>\C</m>, prove that the Gaussian Integers are a ring (don't appeal to <xref ref="thm_subringTest"/>).
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use the <xref ref="thm_subringTest"/> to prove that the Gaussian Integers are a ring.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute the units in <m>\Z[i]</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the set of <m>2\times 2</m> matrices with real entries, <m>M_2(\mathbb{R})</m>, as in <xref ref="ex_M2R"/>. 
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Prove <m>M_2(\mathbb{R})</m> is a ring with the usual matrix addition and matrix multiplication.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              What is special about <m>\R</m>? Does your proof work if <m>\R</m> is replaced by an arbitrary ring <m>R</m>?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              What is special about <m>2</m>? What about the set of <m>n\times n</m> matrices with entries in a ring <m>R</m>, denoted <m>M_n(R)</m>?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove the set of integer multiples of <m>3</m>: 
          <me>3\mathbb{Z} = \{3k\mid k\in\mathbb{Z}\}</me> 
          is a rng but not a ring. You can appeal to the subrng test but also be able to do it straight from the definition.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that in a ring (or rng), the additive identity is unique.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that in a ring (or rng), the multiplicative identity is unique.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that in a ring (or rng), the product of the additive identity and any element is 0.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exer_upperTriangularMatrices">
      <title>Upper Triangular Matrices</title>
      <!-- <notation>
        <usage>UT_n(R)</usage>
        <description>Upper Triangular Matrices</description>
      </notation> -->
      <idx><h>Upper Triangular Matrices</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the subring test to prove that the collection of upper triangular matrices <m>2\times 2</m>-matrices over a general ring 
          <m>R</m>, denoted <m>UT_2(R)</m> forms a ring. An upper triangular <m>2\times2</m>-matrix looks like 
          <me>\begin{bmatrix}
            a \amp b \\ 0_R \amp c
            \end{bmatrix}
          </me>
          where <m>a,b,c\in R</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <idx><h>Lower Triangular Matrices</h></idx>
    <statement>
      <p>
        How would the previous proof change with Lower Triangular Matrices?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Explain why the set of <m>2\times 2</m> upper uni-triangular matrices with coefficients in a ring <m>R</m> is not a ring. A <m>2\times2</m>
        upper uni-triangular matrix is a matrix of the form:
        <me>\begin{bmatrix}
          1_R \amp a \\ 0_R \amp 1_R
          \end{bmatrix}
        </me>
        where <m>a\in R</m>. 
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider the subset <m>R\subseteq M_2(\Q)</m> defined by:
        <me>
          R = \left\{\begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ 0 \amp c\end{bmatrix}\mid a\in\Z, b,c\in\Q \right\}
        </me>
        Prove that <m>R</m> is a subring of <m>M_2(\Q)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        In contrast to the previous example, show that the subset <m>S\subset M_2(\Q)</m> defined by
        <me>
          S = \left\{\begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ 0 \amp c\end{bmatrix}\mid a,c\in\Z, b\in\Q \right\}
        </me>
        is not a subring of <m>M_2(\Q)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
</exercises>
